Answer:

Compressed files take up less storage space than uncompressed files and use less bandwidth when transferred over the network. This is why these data files are distributed as â.csv.gzâ files instead of â.csvâ files.

  1. Briefly describe what Bash commands zcat, zless, zmore, and zgrep do.

    zcat:

    âzcatâ can display the contents of compressed files without actually decompressing it.

    zless:

    âzlessâ can display the contents of compressed files in a scrollable manner without actually decompressing it.

    zmore:

    âzmoreâ can display the contents of compressed files line by line without actually decompressing it.

    zgrep:

    âzgrepâ can extract a specific string or pattern within a compressed files without actually decompressing it.

  1. To compress, or not to compress. Thatâs the question. Letâs focus on the big data file labevents.csv.gz. Compare compressed gz file size to the uncompressed file size. Compare the run times of zcat < ~/mimic/labevents.csv.gz | wc -l versus wc -l labevents.csv. Discuss the trade off between storage and speed for big data files. (Hint: gzip -dk < FILENAME.gz > ./FILENAME. Remember to delete the large labevents.csv file after the exercise.)

Compressed gz file size:

ls -lh ~/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv.gz
-rw-rw-r--@ 1 hiroyasuando  staff   1.8G Jan  5  2023 /Users/hiroyasuando/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv.gz

Uncompressed file size:

ls -lh ~/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv
-rw-rw-r--  1 hiroyasuando  staff    13G Jan  5  2023 /Users/hiroyasuando/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv

Run times of compressed gz file:

time zcat < ~/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv.gz | wc -l
 118171368

real    0m18.917s
user    0m23.030s
sys 0m1.996s

Run times of uncompressed file:

time wc -l ~/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv
 118171368 /Users/hiroyasuando/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv

real    0m5.961s
user    0m4.309s
sys 0m1.437s

Conclusion:

Compressed gz file doesnât take up much storage space, but it takes longer to run. Uncompressed file takes up more storage space, but it takes shorter to run. Itâs a trade off between storage and speed for big data files.

Q4. Whoâs popular in Price and Prejudice

  1. You and your friend just have finished reading Pride and Prejudice by Jane Austen. Among the four main characters in the book, Elizabeth, Jane, Lydia, and Darcy, your friend thinks that Darcy was the most mentioned. You, however, are certain it was Elizabeth. Obtain the full text of the novel from http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/42671/pg42671.txt and save to your local folder.
wget -nc http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/42671/pg42671.txt 
File âpg42671.txtâ already there; not retrieving.
Explain what wget -nc does. Do not put this text file pg42671.txt in Git.

Explanation:

âwgetâ downloads files from some URL. â-ncâ means only if the file doesnât already exist locally or if the local file has to be updated, the file will be downloaded.

Complete the following loop to tabulate the number of times each of the four characters is mentioned using Linux commands.

# Check
#wget -nc http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/42671/pg42671.txt
for char in Elizabeth Jane Lydia Darcy
do
  echo $char:
  grep -i $char pg42671.txt | wc -l 
done
Elizabeth:
     633
Jane:
     289
Lydia:
     167
Darcy:
     415
  1. Whatâs the difference between the following two commands?
echo 'hello, world' > test1.txt

and

echo 'hello, world' >> test2.txt

Explanation:

echo âhello, worldâ > test1.txt:

This command will create or overwrite a file called âtest1.txtâ and write âhello, worldâ in it.

echo âhello, worldâ >> test2.txt:

This command will append âhello, worldâ in the last line of the file in the existing âtest2.txtâ file. If the âtest2.txtâ file does not exist, this command makes âtest2.txtâ and write âhello, worldâ in it.

  1. Using your favorite text editor (e.g., vi), type the following and save the file as middle.sh:
#!/bin/sh
# Select lines from the middle of a file.
# Usage: bash middle.sh filename end_line num_lines
head -n "$2" "$1" | tail -n "$3"

Using chmod to make the file executable by the owner, and run

chmod u+x middle.sh
./middle.sh pg42671.txt 20 5
Editor: R. W. Chapman

Release date: May 9, 2013 [eBook #42671]

Language: English

Explain the output. Explain the meaning of "$1", "$2", and "$3" in this shell script. Why do we need the first line of the shell script?

Explanation: This script takes the first 20 lines of the file âpg42671.txtâ and then takes the last 5 lines of the first 20 lines, which is the output.

$1 specifies a file. $2 specifies the end line you extract. $3 specifies the number of lines you extract. The first line of the shell script is called âshebangâ and it tells the computer which interpreter to use to execute the script.

Q6. Book

  1. Git clone the repository https://github.com/christophergandrud/Rep-Res-Book for the book Reproducible Research with R and RStudio to your local machine.

    I did it.

  2. Open the project by clicking rep-res-3rd-edition.Rproj and compile the book by clicking Build Book in the Build panel of RStudio. (Hint: I was able to build git_book and epub_book but not pdf_book.)

    I did it.

The point of this exercise is (1) to get the book for free and (2) to see an example how a complicated project such as a book can be organized in a reproducible way.
